ce:section.ce:para:
Fig. 2
 shows that B- and N-doping induced different degrees of localization in the FMOs (see also Fig. 3
). In the case of B-doping, an additional hole level is introduced into the bandgap of the GQD because B is a p-type dopant, which lowered the Fermi level due to the higher electronegativity of the carbon atom compared to the boron atom. The positive electron induction effect of boron increases the density of the π-electron cloud in the FMOs and shifts them to lower energy levels. Consequently, it breaks the degeneracy of the LUMO/LUMO+1 orbitals and stabilizes the LUMO orbital, leading to the appearance of the midgap states (TCB) in the unoccupied energy levels. In the case of N-doping, the additional electronic level is introduced into the bandgap of the GQD because the N atom is an n-type dopant, which raises the Fermi level. As a result, the degeneracy of the HOMO/HOMO-1 orbitals is removed, and the HOMO orbital destabilizes, leading to the appearance of the semi-degenerate midgap states (TVB) in the occupied energy levels. In addition, the TCB is located near the HOMO level, while the TVB is located near the LUMO level. This is because the P-type dopant induces additional hole states in the bandgap of the semiconductor and traps electrons. Therefore, the TCB is closer to the HOMO than to the LUMO in B-GQDs because the large energy gap between the TCB and the LUMO can trap electrons. Similarly, the N-type dopant induces additional electronic states in the bandgap of the semiconductor and traps holes. Therefore, the TVB in N-GQDs is closer to the LUMO than to HOMO, because this creates the large energy gap between the TVB and HOMO, which serves to trap holes.
